# Packet 013: Neuroscience and Mechanistic-Interpretability Receipts

Status: `HYPOTHESIS`

## Market Context

Mechanistic interpretability has moved from toy models into production-scale systems. A 2026 arXiv paper reports sparse autoencoders with up to 34 million features on Claude 3 Sonnet activations, with multilingual and multimodal feature behavior, behavior steering, and safety-relevant features. The same abstract states major limitations: incomplete features and lack of rigorous methods for evaluating whether features faithfully capture model computations.

Source URL: https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.29358

## Telos Wedge

Hypothesis: interpretability and neuroscience-adjacent AI work need `MechanismEvidencePacket` objects:

- model identity and activation source;
- feature extraction method;
- training data and sampling boundaries;
- feature examples and labels;
- intervention or causal evidence;
- evaluator identity, prompts, and scores;
- limitations;
- reproducibility artifacts;
- claim label: `observed`, `causal-probe`, `interpreted`, `faithfulness-unverified`.

This connects to neuroscience because brain-scale foundation models and neural activity models face the same hard question: what is an observed representation versus a proven mechanism?

